"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105787","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-12-01","<p>We are currently considering the form and timing of the public consultation in the light of ongoing caste discrimination litigation in the Employment Appeal Tribunal. We will await the outcome of the judgment before deciding in what form to issue the public consultation.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Garden of Frognal",,"2014-12-01T16:36:05.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105787/answer","Biography information for Baroness Garden of Frognal","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105787/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105787/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-03","Castes: Discrimination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to launch a further public consultation on treatment of caste-based discrimination as an aspect of race within the meaning of the Equality Act 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL2600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105788","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-17","<p /> <p>The Government has consulted on whether the law should be changed to allow legally valid humanist and potentially other non-religious belief marriages. We are considering the responses we received and the implications for marriage law and practice if a change were to be made. We plan to publish the Government’s response to the review before 1 January 2015.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2014-11-17T16:28:44.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105788/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105788/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105788/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-03","Marriage","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to introduce legislation enabling humanist marriages to be recognised.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL2601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105789","Home Office","false","2014-11-11","<p>Investigative activity involving interference with property or wireless telegraphy, such as International Mobile Subscriber Identity (IMSI) grabbers, is regulated by the Police Act 1997 and the Intelligence Services Act 1994 which sets out the high level of authorisation required before the police or Security and intelligence agencies can undertake such activity. Use of these powers is overseen by the Intelligence Services Commissioner and the Office of Surveillance Commissioners. In any case involving the interception of the content of a communication, a warrant authorised by the Secretary of State under the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000 is required.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2014-11-11T16:53:45.2761824Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105789/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105789/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105789/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-03","Electronic Surveillance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what are the safeguards against the misuse by the police and other public authorities of International Mobile Subscriber Identity Catcher devices to intercept and listen to phone calls, collect and read text messages and emails, and block phone calls in a specific area.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL2602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105790","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-17","<p /> <p>There have always been controls on the sending of parcels into prisons; the revised Incentives and Earned Privileges (IEP) national policy framework has simply ensured greater consistency across the prison estate. We now have simple rules that allow prisoners a parcel of items when they first arrive in prison, and then only further items in exceptional circumstances. The restrictions were introduced to enhance existing security measures and to prevent the IEP policy framework from being undermined.</p><p> </p><p>There is no longer a numerical limit on the amount of underwear that prisoners can have in possession; the amount they can have is subject only to overarching volumetric control limits.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2014-11-17T16:19:40.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105790/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105790/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105790/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-03","Prisons: Parcels","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the effects of the ban on the receipt by prisoners in England and Wales of parcels containing for example books, underwear, clothing, stationery and Christmas presents.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL2603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105791","Home Office","false","2014-11-18","<p>The Government is clear that domestic violence and abuse does not just mean physical violence. It can also involve coercive and controlling behaviour, including dowry abuse and other forms of financial abuse. The cross-Government definition of domestic violence and abuse encompasses, but is not limited to, psychological, physical, sexual, financial and emotional abuse. This definition is used by Government departments to inform policy development, and other agencies, such as the police, to inform the identification of domestic violence cases.</p><p>We have recently consulted on strengthening the law around domestic violence and abuse and are considering our response. Our consideration will include whether there should be a specific offence of domestic abuse and if so, what patterns of behaviour should constitute such abuse.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2550","2014-11-18T15:10:01.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105791/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105791/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105791/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-03","Marriage","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to consider introducing legislation in England and Wales similar to India’s Dowry Prohibition Act 1961 so as to prohibit the giving or taking of a dowry, and India’s Domestic Violence Act 2005 so as to treat demanding a dowry as domestic violence.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL2604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105793","Department for Education","false","2014-11-17","<p>Parents can make their own arrangements for their child’s education. These must be suitable for the child’s age, aptitude and any special educational needs they may have.</p><p> </p><p>Under the Children and Families Act 2014 where a local authority maintains an Education, Health and Care (EHC) plan for a child or young person it is under a duty to secure the special educational provision specified in it unless parents have made suitable alternative arrangements.</p><p> </p><p>Where a local authority is satisfied that the parents’ arrangements are suitable it must continue to review the child’s EHC plan annually and assure itself that the plan remains appropriate.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2014-11-17T14:20:33.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105793/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105793/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-03","Special Educational Needs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, under the Children and Families Act 2014, a family with a child who has special educational needs may opt out of an Education and Health Care Plan; and, if so, by what mechanism.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL2605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105794","Department for Education","false","2014-11-17","<p>Social services investigations into families are not automatically triggered if a family whose child has an Education, Health and Care Needs Assessment chooses to educate their child at home. Under section 7 of the Education Act 1996, parents have the right to educate their child at home. Home education must be suitable to the child’s age, ability, aptitude and special educational needs.</p><p> </p><p>Where local authorities and parents agree that home education is the right provision for a child with an Education, Health and Care (EHC) plan, the plan should make clear that the child will be educated at home. If it does, the local authority must arrange the special educational provision in the plan, working with the parents.</p><p> </p><p>In cases where the local authority names a school or type of school that it considers appropriate in the child’s EHC plan but the parents decided to educate the child at home, the local authority is not under a duty to arrange the special educational provision specified in the plan provided that it is satisfied that the arrangements made by the parents are suitable. Local authorities do not have the right of entry to the family home to check that the provision being made by the parent is suitable and may only enter the home at the invitation of the parents.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2014-11-17T14:19:59.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105794/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105794/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-03","Special Educational Needs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether social services investigations into families are automatically triggered if a family chooses an educational method, such as home education, other than those listed in their Education and Health Care Assessment.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL2606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105795","Department of Health","false","2014-11-17","<p>There are no licensing requirements to open a private dispensing appliance contractor business. NHS England is responsible for determining whether a dispensing appliance contractor should be granted the right to provide National Health Service pharmaceutical services. Such determinations can generally be appealed to the Family Health Services Appeal Unit of the NHS Litigation Authority.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department keeps the operation of the relevant NHS regulations governing the right to provide NHS pharmaceutical services under regular review with NHS England, the NHS Litigation Authority and contractors’ representatives, as appropriate. We are not aware of any significant issues regarding the impact of these arrangements on small and medium-sized businesses offering continence products nor on the adoption of innovation in the NHS.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL2608 ; HL2609","2014-11-17T12:48:02.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105795/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105795/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105795/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-03","Medical Equipment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to assess the impact of the process of obtaining Dispensing Appliance Contractor licences on the Department of Health’s wish to increase medical innovation, as outlined in their Innovation Health and Wealth strategy.","false","Biography information for Lord Swinfen",,"Lord Swinfen","HL2607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105797","Department of Health","false","2014-11-17","<p>There are no licensing requirements to open a private dispensing appliance contractor business. NHS England is responsible for determining whether a dispensing appliance contractor should be granted the right to provide National Health Service pharmaceutical services. Such determinations can generally be appealed to the Family Health Services Appeal Unit of the NHS Litigation Authority.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department keeps the operation of the relevant NHS regulations governing the right to provide NHS pharmaceutical services under regular review with NHS England, the NHS Litigation Authority and contractors’ representatives, as appropriate. We are not aware of any significant issues regarding the impact of these arrangements on small and medium-sized businesses offering continence products nor on the adoption of innovation in the NHS.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL2607 ; HL2609","2014-11-17T12:48:02.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105797/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105797/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105797/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-03","Incontinence: Medical Equipment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to assess the impact of the process of obtaining Dispensing Appliance Contractor licences on small and medium-sized businesses offering continence products.","false","Biography information for Lord Swinfen",,"Lord Swinfen","HL2608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105799","Department of Health","false","2014-11-17","<p>There are no licensing requirements to open a private dispensing appliance contractor business. NHS England is responsible for determining whether a dispensing appliance contractor should be granted the right to provide National Health Service pharmaceutical services. Such determinations can generally be appealed to the Family Health Services Appeal Unit of the NHS Litigation Authority.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department keeps the operation of the relevant NHS regulations governing the right to provide NHS pharmaceutical services under regular review with NHS England, the NHS Litigation Authority and contractors’ representatives, as appropriate. We are not aware of any significant issues regarding the impact of these arrangements on small and medium-sized businesses offering continence products nor on the adoption of innovation in the NHS.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL2607 ; HL2608","2014-11-17T12:48:01.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105799/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105799/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-03","Medical Equipment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government who holds primary responsibility for issuing Dispensing Appliance Contractor licences.","false","Biography information for Lord Swinfen",,"Lord Swinfen","HL2609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105800","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-17","<p>The United Kingdom’s net contributions to the EU Budget over the period 2009-10 to 2013-14 were £41.1 billion. The current forecast for 2014-15 by the Office for Budget Responsibility is £9.1 billion.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All data can be found in Table C.1 of HM Treasury’s Public Expenditure Statistical Analyses of July 2014[1].</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Contributions to the EU Budget are financed from Traditional Own Resources (mainly customs duties and sugar levies), contributions based on a hypothetical harmonised VAT base, and Gross National Income based contributions.</p><p> </p><p>-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/public-expenditure-statistical-analyses-2014" target="_blank"><strong>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/public-expenditure-statistical-analyses-2014</strong></a></p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Deighton",,"2014-11-17T17:57:32.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105800/answer","Biography information for Lord Deighton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105800/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-03","EU Budget: Contributions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the total amount of the United Kingdom net contributions paid to the European Union budget in the years 2010–13 inclusive; what is the estimated total for 2014; and how those contributions are financed.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL2610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105802","Department for International Development","false","2014-11-17","<p>The UK has contributed £1,587 million to the European Development Fund 2010-2013 inclusive. The estimated total for 2014 is £326 million, subject to exchange rates. The contributions are financed from the DFID budget.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Northover",,"2014-11-17T17:24:51.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105802/answer","Biography information for Baroness Northover","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105802/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105802/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-11-03","European Union","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the total cost of contributions paid by the United Kingdom to European Union programmes falling outside the European Union budget in the years 2010–13 inclusive; what is the estimated total for 2014; and how those contributions are financed.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL2611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105803","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-17","<p>The Council of Europe's budget for 2014 is €402,694,300, financed by member states according to an agreed formula based on population and gross domestic product. The UK’s contribution for 2014 is €31,086,578. The European Court of Human Rights is financed from this overall budget. For 2014 the Court budget was €67,650,400.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2014-11-17T16:26:42.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105803/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105803/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-03","Council of Europe","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the annual United Kingdom contribution to the Council of Europe, including the costs of the European Court of Human Rights; and how they are financed.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL2612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105805","Department for International Development","false","2014-11-11","<p>Overseas Development Assistance (ODA) is reported by the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development’s Development Assistance Committee (OECD DAC) through its donor states as a proportion of Gross National Income (GNI). DFID calculates ODA disbursements to measure its stated goal of achieving 0.7% during 2013 and in order that international comparisons can be made with other DAC donor states.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The average ODA to GNI ratio for 2013 for all DAC donor states is 0.397%. The UK GNI for 2013 (using the ESA95 unadjusted for (Eurostat) reservations methodology) was £1,622,166m. If the average percentage were applied, the UK contribution would be £6,437m.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Northover",,"2014-11-11T16:26:23.0241772Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105805/answer","Biography information for Baroness Northover","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105805/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105805/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-11-03","Development Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the latest figure of the annual average percentage of gross domestic product paid by contributing countries in official development assistance; and what would be the cost to the United Kingdom if it used that average in assessing its own aid programme.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL2613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105806","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-11-20","<p>Each year the Department of Energy and Climate change publishes estimates of UK oil reserves based on assessments of the amount of oil that is technically and commercially recoverable. The judgement on commerciality rests with the operators of each field/discovery, not the Department. It will depend, among other things, on oil prices when they make that assessment. The latest estimates can be found on the attached.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2014-11-20T16:49:22.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105806/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105806/answer","UK Oil Reserves and Estimated Ultimate Recovery 2014.pdf","UK Oil Reserves and Estimated Ultimate Recovery 2014.pdf","UK Oil Reserves & Estimated Ultimate Recovery 2014","UK Oil Reserves & Estimated Ultimate Recovery 2014","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105806/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-03","North Sea Oil","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the effect of changing oil prices on reserves from North Sea oil.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL2614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105808","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-17","<p>Kosovo Force (KFOR) continues to have a Kosovo-wide role particularly in the Serbian majority north of Kosovo. It also has a specific role in protecting Serbian Orthodox sites, yet in the south of Kosovo this is coming to an end. KFOR is currently in the process of transferring responsibility for these sites to the Kosovo Police. This is done in consultation with the Serbian Orthodox Church and taking into account the political and security conditions on the ground. The monastery at Decani remains under KFOR protection and the Patriarchate in Peja is currently undergoing a transition to police protection.</p><p>While there has been a slight increase in incidents of intercommunal violence, mainly due to the reverberations following a recent football match between Albania and Serbia, we do not see an overall trend of an increase in violence in general or a need for KFOR to increase activity.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2014-11-17T14:40:52.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105808/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105808/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105808/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-03","Kosovo","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps the Kosovo Force is taking to prevent intercommunal violence in Kosovo; and whether they consider that it should increase its activity.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105809","Department for International Development","false","2014-11-11","<p>Disbursement of pledges has already begun, funding early relief, recovery and reconstruction interventions in accordance with the multi-phased strategy set out in the Palestinian Authority-led Early Recovery and Reconstruction Plan 2014-2017. The Palestinian Authority will oversee the implementation of the plan in coordination with the UN, donors, international financial institutions, civil society and the private sector.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Northover",,"2014-11-11T16:27:53.5612626Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105809/answer","Biography information for Baroness Northover","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105809/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-11-03","Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect payments of the $5.4 billion pledged for reconstruction in Gaza to begin; and who will be responsible for collecting the pledges, and for supervising payments for work done.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105810","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-11","<p>The British Government is concerned about reports of kidnapping in Egypt. We have been clear throughout recent events in Egypt that freedoms in the Egyptian constitution, including of religious belief, need to be protected as a vital component of a democratic society. Most recently, the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), and the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my hon. Friend the Member for Bournemouth East (Mr Ellwood), raised the need to protect human rights in their meeting with the Egyptian Foreign Minister on 27 October.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2014-11-11T16:10:46.2842658Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105810/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105810/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105810/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-03","Egypt","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Egypt about recent kidnappings, in particular of women and children in central and upper Egypt, allegedly for forced conversion and marriage.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105811","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-11","<p>The Armed Forces operate 14 Field Hospitals: three Regular Army, ten Regionally Recruited Reserve Field Hospitals and one Nationally Recruited Reserve Field Hospital. These are shown below:</p><p>22 Field Hospital (Regular) - presently deployed in Sierra Leone</p><p>33 Field Hospital (Regular)</p><p>34 Field Hospital (Regular)</p><p>201 (Northern) Field Hospital (Reserve)</p><p>202 (Midlands) Field Hospital (Reserve)</p><p>203 (Welsh) Field Hospital (Reserve)</p><p>204 (North Irish) Field Hospital (Reserve)</p><p>205 (Scottish) Field Hospital (Reserve)</p><p>207 (Manchester) Field Hospital (Reserve)</p><p>208 (Merseyside) Field Hospital (Reserve)</p><p>212 (Yorkshire) Field Hospital (Reserve)</p><p>243 (Wessex) Field Hospital (Reserve)</p><p>256 (London) Field Hospital (Reserve)</p><p>306 Hospital Support Regiment (Reserve)</p><p>Regular Field Hospitals have a permanent cadre of staff who maintain the hospital and its equipment in barracks. During deployments and exercises they are augmented with Regular clinical staff from the Joint Medical Command. At the highest level of readiness, one of these units is able to deploy its lead elements at five days notice.</p><p>The Reserve Field Hospitals' role is to be ready to deploy for enduring operations with a minimum of 18 months notice. This allows sufficient time to prepare both the manpower and equipment for the deployment. Reserves can and do also volunteer as individuals to deploy on operations with Regular units at shorter notice.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Astor of Hever",,"2014-11-11T17:16:43.0946034Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105811/answer","Biography information for Lord Astor of Hever","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105811/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-03","Armed Forces: Hospitals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many staffed and equipped field hospitals they have.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105812","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-06","<p>The Government has named 30 employers under the revised Naming and Shaming Scheme. Between them they owed workers a total of over £50,000 in arrears and have been charged financial penalties totalling over £24,000. Details of these employers can be found on the original press notices (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/government-gets-tough-with-employers-failing-to-pay-minimum-wage" target="_blank">28 February 2014</a> and <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/government-names-employers-who-fail-to-pay-minimum-wage" target="_blank">8 June 2014</a>), including the town in which the employer is based. However, these organisations may employ staff or have offices or other operations in other geographical locations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>No employers have been prosecuted under the National Minimum Wage Act since October 2013.</p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-11-06T16:01:40.3097074Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105812/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105812/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-03","Business: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many employers in (a) the North West and (b) Warrington have been (i) named and (ii) prosecuted since 1 October 2013.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","212902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105813","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-10","<p>My Rt. Hon. Friend the then Minister for Skills and Enterprise (Matthew Hancock) met with the four nation Ministers including Dr Stephen Farry, MLA, Minister for Employment and Learning, on 19 June 2014.</p><p>He updated Ministers on the review of apprenticeships and trailblazer reforms in England.</p><p>Dr Stephen Farry informed Ministers that Northern Ireland would be producing a new strategy on apprenticeships and this was formally announced on 24 June 2014.</p><p>Ministers agreed that an official-level group would be beneficial and my Rt. Hon. Friend. the now Minister for Business and Energy Matthew Hancock suggested extending the remit of the UK strategic policy forum to include apprenticeships. The UK Strategic Forum meets approximately one month prior to the four nation Ministerial meetings and the first meeting took place on 4 June 2014.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-11-10T12:43:40.4812171Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105813/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105813/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-03","Apprentices: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent discussions he has had with Ministers in the Northern Ireland Executive on encouraging businesses to offer apprenticeships to young people.","false","Biography information for Lord McCrea of Magherafelt and Cookstown","South Antrim","Dr William McCrea","212916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105814","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-17","<p>London is the tech capital of Europe. The Government has played a key part in its success. It supports Tech City UK which delivers support services and programmes to tech businesses in London and UK-wide. London and Partners promotes the London wide tech sector, working on behalf of the Mayor of London and other commercial partners, including Tech City for which it took over specific responsibility in April this year.</p><p> </p><p>Technology companies in London will benefit from a range of government funding such as the:</p><p> </p><p>• recently announced 5m funding (£2m in 2015/2016 and a provisional allocation of £3m in 2016/17) for a pilot digital skills programme to be run by the London Enterprise Panel as part of the London Growth Deal.</p><p> </p><p>• A new Digital Catapult, located in King’s Cross, with £50m over 5 years to provide tech companies with access to expertise and enable them to develop new products and services.</p><p> </p><p>• £40K, this financial year, for Tech City UK’s Future Fifty Programme. Of the 50 tech companies, 37 of them are headquartered in London.</p><p> </p><p>• £400K this financial year for Tech City UK’s Digital Business Academy - an online training programme to ensure everyone has the much needed digital skills.</p><p> </p><p>We will have the lowest corporation tax rate in the G7 from next year. Technology companies can also benefit from other tax incentives such as the Patent Box, which can give an effective 10% tax rate for qualifying net revenue arising from EU or UK registered patents, R&amp;D tax credits, the Enterprise Investment Scheme and the Seed Enterprise Investment Scheme.</p><p> </p><p>The Government launched the new computing curriculum in September 2014, to ensure a pipeline of digitally skilled individuals. £3.5m of funding has been provided to ensure teachers have the skills to teach the curriculum and there are a number of coding clubs available in London schools, to inspire young people about the career opportunities digital skills provide.</p><p> </p><p>There is also good work at a local level, for example, Camden Council has started to set up code clubs in schools, see the following link: <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/local-government-network/2013/sep/02/camden-council-pioneers-coding-in-schools" target="_blank">http://www.theguardian.com/local-government-network/2013/sep/02/camden-council-pioneers-coding-in-schools</a></p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-11-17T17:06:59.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105814/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105814/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-03","Technology: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what future investment the Government plans to make to promote the technology sector in London.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","212963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105815","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-06","<p>Details of the employers that have already been named under the BIS Naming Scheme can be found on the original press notices (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/government-gets-tough-with-employers-failing-to-pay-minimum-wage" target="_blank">28 February 2014</a> and <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/government-names-employers-who-fail-to-pay-minimum-wage" target="_blank">8 June 2014</a>).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information about individual companies, including registration numbers, is available through the Companies House website <a href="http://www.companieshouse.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.companieshouse.gov.uk</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Any worker who believes that they are being paid below the minimum wage should call the Pay &amp; Work Rights Helpline on 0800 917 2368. HM Revenue &amp; Customs investigate all complaints.</p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-11-06T17:29:40.4237432Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105815/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105815/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-03","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the company registration number is of (a) Master Distribution Limited, Essex and (b) Zoom Limited, Havant, named for non-payment of the national minimum wage in his Department's press notice of 8 June 2014.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","212931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105816","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-06","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>No licences granted to companies to export dual-use chemicals that could be used as precursors to the production of chemical weapons to Syria remain in place.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-11-06T15:57:24.5942488Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105816/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105816/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-03","Chemicals: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether licences grated to companies to export dual-use chemicals that could be used as precursors to the production of chemical weapons to Syria remain in place.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","213006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105817","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-06","<p>The names of the companies which had licences approved to export dual-use chemicals that could be used as precursors to the production of chemical weapons to Syria cannot be disclosed. Following an assessment under the terms of the Freedom of Information Act the public interest, in the maintenance of the confidentiality and overall integrity of the export licensing system, on this occasion outweighs the public interest in the disclosure of the name of the exporter.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-11-06T15:56:08.4595502Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105817/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105817/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-03","Chemicals: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make public the names of the companies which had licences approved to export dual-use chemicals that could be used as precursors to the production of chemical weapons to Syria.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","213007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105818","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-10","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer I gave on 14 July 2014, Official Report Col 537W.</p><p> </p><p>Although the Hon. Member has requested information in respect of a slightly shorter period (i.e. since 2010 and not each of the past 5 years) and has asked about fees over the prevention of release of information requested by Freedom of Information requests rather than in relation to freedom of information cases generally, the answer remains the same as that previously given.</p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-11-10T16:42:01.2165942Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105818/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105818/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-03","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much his Department has spent on legal fees over prevention of release of information requested by Freedom of Information requests since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105819","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Department has made 269 appointments by exception since April 2011. Centrally held records are not available prior to April 2011.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not release the name of individuals appointed to posts.</p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-11-10T15:58:05.8440936Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105819/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105819/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-03","Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, on how many occasions his Department has made appointments by exception since 2010; and who was appointed for each such post.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105820","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-10","<p>An element of the Department’s overall pay bill for staff below the Senior Civil Service (SCS) is allocated to payments related directly to performance. There are two types of award:</p><p> </p><ol start="1" type="1"><li>Annual performance awards, that reward staff based on their annual performance rating.</li><li>In-year awards that recognise strong performance in particularly demanding tasks or situations. These can be in the form of cash payments or vouchers.</li></ol><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These non-consolidated, non-pensionable one-off payments are used to drive high performance in the department and do not add to future pay bills.</p><p> </p><p>Details of the number and cost of in-year awards in 2013, and until the end of September in 2014 are contained in table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Cash Awards</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Value of Cash Awards</strong></p><p><strong>(£)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Vouchers</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Value of Vouchers</strong></p><p><strong>(£)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>1,489</p></td><td><p>434,743</p></td><td><p>803</p></td><td><p>32,110</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014*</p></td><td><p>1,145</p></td><td><p>353,200</p></td><td><p>788</p></td><td><p>41,525</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>* Jan – Sept 2014</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-11-10T15:48:11.0399721Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105820/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105820/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-03","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many Instant Rewards of what value were given to his Department's officials in (a) 2013 and (b) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105821","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Civil Service Commission publish details of appointments made by exception and approved by them in their annual reports and on their website. These reports are available in the Library of the House. It would not be appropriate to publish details of the requests turned down by the Commission as the numbers involved are so small.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-11-10T15:49:40.309095Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105821/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105821/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-03","Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, on how many occasions his Department has had requests for appointments by exception to the Senior Civil Service turned down by the Civil Service Commission since 2010; and who was appointed for each such post.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105822","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-10","<p>Statistics on the Freedom of Information performance of Government Departments since January 2010 are published by the Ministry of Justice. They are available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/government-foi-statistics#2010-2012" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/government-foi-statistics#2010-2012</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The published statistics include the numbers of requests received by each Department, the numbers answered in full and where information was partly or fully withheld.</p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-11-10T14:37:50.9683071Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105822/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105822/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-03","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many Freedom of Information requests his Department has declined to answer in full since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105823","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-06","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Applications to export dual use chemicals to Syria were assessed thoroughly against strict licensing criteria, drawing on open source and classified information. However, the licences were revoked following a revision to the sanctions regime which came into force on 17 June 2012. No goods were exported to Syria under these licences before they were revoked.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-11-06T15:51:29.7796521Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105823/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105823/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-03","Chemicals: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he took to ensure that the export licences approved to export to Syria dual-use chemicals that could be used as precursors to the production of chemical weapons would not be used for this purpose.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","213138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105824","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-10","<p>In 2012, the Department (including our UKTI organisation), purchased 13 iPhones at £360 each, through our framework contract with Vodafone. The call costs for each of those phones would have been absorbed into the standard mobile telephony running cost budget and so aren't identified individually.</p><p>Our corporate Smart Phone service is not predicated on iPhone technology and so no further purchases have been made to date.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-11-10T16:03:50.3947878Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105824/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105824/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-03","Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much his Department spent on iPhones in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105825","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office.</p><p>This Government is determined to provide staff with technology that allows them to do their job effectively and efficiently. As was the case under the previous administration, staff can be provided with such equipment when there is an appropriate business need.</p><p>The total expenditure in each year since 2010 is;</p><p>● 2010 £0</p><p>● 2011 £0</p><p>● 2012 £24,320</p><p>● 2013 £24,320</p><p>● 2014 £34,050</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-11-10T14:59:37.6000427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105825/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105825/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-03","Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much his Department spent on iPhones in each year since 2010; and how much was spent on iPhones by 10 Downing Street in each such year.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105826","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Committee for the Grant of Honours, Decorations and Medals (HD Committee) has recently, as part of the Independent Military Medals Review, considered the proposals to institute a National Defence Medal and a Nuclear Test Veterans Medal. HD Committee considered the merits of both medals but in respect of the latter concluded that this was not the sort of operational duty that would normally be recognised by the award of a medal; and that a strong enough case could not be made at this time for a National Defence Medal.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-11-10T14:56:49.6964496Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105826/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105826/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-03","Military Decorations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will establish a Committee on the Grant of Honours, Decorations and Medals to consider representations from those who support the creation of a (a) National Defence Medal and (b) Nuclear Test Veterans Medal.","false","Biography information for Dr Eilidh Whiteford","Banff and Buchan","Dr Eilidh Whiteford","213143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105827","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office.</p><p>Cabinet Office makes appointments on merit on the basis of fair and open competition in compliance with the Civil Service Commission’s Recruitment Principles.</p><p>Other appointments are made using permitted exceptions to the Civil Service Commission’s Recruitment Principles to support Apprenticeship and Graduate Internship schemes, commercial interchange, short term projects and other specific business needs.</p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>47</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>78</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>126</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>94</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014- 31/10/14</p></td><td><p>110</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>In line with the practice of the previous administration the names of individuals have not been provided to protect their identities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","213033","2014-11-10T17:42:36.5611814Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105827/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105827/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-03","Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, on how many occasions his Department has made appointments by exception since 2010; and who was appointed for each such post.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105828","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-07","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office. Information on departments’ handling of FOI requests is published on a quarterly basis by the Ministry of Justice and is available at GOV.UK under the series Government FOI Statistics.</p><p>I refer the hon. Member to the answers I gave on 10 July 2014 to UIN: PQ204306-PQ20470.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","213093 ; 213101 ; 213114","2014-11-07T11:47:51.9780741Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105828/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105828/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-03","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many Freedom of Information requests his Department has declined to answer in full since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105829","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-06","<p>The Cabinet Office has appointed Ipsos MORI and NEF Consulting to carry out an evaluation of the Community Organisers programme.</p><p>A recent interim report will be placed in the House of Commons Library.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2014-11-06T16:36:49.3422397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105829/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105829/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-03","Community Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent analysis of the performance of the Community Organisers Programme has been conducted.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","213129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105830","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-06","<p>Over the lifetime of this parliament, a total of £25.5m has been allocated to the Community Organisers programme from the budget of the Office for Civil Society.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2014-11-06T16:26:07.6110182Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105830/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105830/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-03","Community Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much of the funding of the Community Organisers Programme was allocated from the Office of Civil Society's budget.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","213130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105831","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office.</p><p>The Civil Service Commission publish details of appointments made by exception and approved by them in their annual reports and on their website. These reports are available in the Library of the House. It would not be appropriate to publish, by Department, details of the requests turned down by the Commission as the numbers involved are so small.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","213053","2014-11-10T14:52:51.1612682Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105831/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105831/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-03","Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, on how many occasions his Department has had requests for appointments by exception to the Senior Civil Service turned down by the Civil Service Commission since 2010; and who was appointed for each such post.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105832","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-06","<p>As the Prime Minister set out in his written statement on 13 October 2014, the Minister for Business and Enterprise as the Government’s Anti-Corruption Champion will oversee the Government response to domestic and international corruption. His appointment demonstrates the Government’s continued commitment to tackling this issue both at home and abroad.</p><p>The Government will publish a cross-departmental anti-corruption plan, setting out the range of activity currently underway and future policy directions, later this year and this will provide further information about the role.</p><p>The Anti-Corruption Champion is supported by officials in both the Cabinet Office and Home Office who lead on the co-ordination of international and domestic anti-corruption work across departments.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-11-06T17:38:29.3063499Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105832/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105832/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-03","Anti-corruption Champion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will place in the Library a copy of the job specification for the role of the Anti-corruption Champion; and what dedicated resources there are to support that role.","false","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","213128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105833","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-07","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office. Information on departments’ handling of FOI requests is published on a quarterly basis by the Ministry of Justice and is available at GOV.UK under the series Government FOI Statistics.</p><p>I refer the hon. Member to the answers I gave on 10 July 2014 to UIN: PQ204306-PQ20470.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","213080 ; 213093 ; 213114","2014-11-07T11:47:52.1577093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105833/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105833/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-03","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much his Department has spent on legal fees over prevention of release of information requested by Freedom of Information requests since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105834","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office. The Cabinet Office does not provide Instant Rewards.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","213073","2014-11-10T14:55:41.253604Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105834/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105834/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-03","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many Instant Rewards of what value were given to his Department's officials in (a) 2013 and (b) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105835","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-11-06","<p>This was a consultation that was carried out by the last Government and the current Government has no plans to publish either the results or a response.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2014-11-06T15:42:47.1807057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105835/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105835/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-11-03","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, if he will publish the results of the Government's 2009 consultation on the edited version of the electoral register and the Government's response to it.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","212872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105837","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-10","<p>A statistical release covering take-up of the Employment Allowance, including regional and constituency data was published on the 7<sup>th</sup> November.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These statistics show that up to October 5<sup>th</sup> 2014, midway through the 2014-15 tax year, 35,000 employers in Wales and 728,000 employers in England had claimed and benefitted from the Employment Allowance. Employers automatically benefit from the allowance if they make a claim and have an employer Class 1 National Insurance Contribution bill.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>So far 900 employers in Aberconwy and 6,400 employers in the North Wales constituencies have benefitted from the Employment Allowance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This demonstrates the Government’s commitment to reducing the costs of employment for small businesses across the UK.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","212969","2014-11-10T17:56:37.332709Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105837/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105837/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-03","National Insurance Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many businesses have (a) claimed and (b) been awarded employment allowance in (i) Wales and (ii) England.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","212884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105838","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-13","<p><strong>The Government has already devolved significant powers and responsibilities to London. The Government passed responsibility for housing, economic development and the Olympic legacy to London through the Localism Act 2011, in addition to transport, planning and the police already controlled by the Mayor. The Government keeps all decisions on tax policy under review.</strong></p>","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Danny Alexander",,"2014-11-13T10:45:37.9469985Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105838/answer","Biography information for Danny Alexander","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105838/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-03","Devolution: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government plans to devolve new fiscal powers to the Greater London Authority.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","212962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105839","HM Treasury","false","2015-01-30","<p>The Government takes the enforcement of the National Minimum Wage very seriously and has increased the financial penalty percentage from 50% to 100% of the unpaid wages owed to workers, and the maximum penalty from £5,000 to £20,000. These new limits are now in force where arrears are identified in pay reference periods on or after 7 March 2014. The Government will also bring in primary legislation as soon as possible so that the maximum £20,000 penalty can apply to each underpaid worker.<br><br>I am unable to provide in-year figures for 2014/15 as HM Revenue and Customs do not disclose results mid-way through a year; this is because the results have not been internally verified. In an effort to assist I have provided the verified figures up to the year 2013/14, which provides numbers of the maximum penalties issued up until April 2014.&quot;</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-01-30T13:58:34.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105839/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105839/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105839/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-03","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many employers were fined the maximum penalty for breaches of the National Minimum Wage Act 1998 in each month of 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","212979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105840","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-06","<p>The Government takes the enforcement of the National Minimum Wage (NMW) very seriously. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) review every complaint that is referred to them by the Pay and Work Rights Helpline. In addition, HMRC undertake targeted enforcement on employers across the United Kingdom who are more likely to be not paying NMW.</p><p> </p><p><strong>HMRC does not keep statistics at a regional level. Many employers' registered trading addresses differ from where they undertake business. Larger employers may be registered under one address but have outlets across the country.</strong></p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-11-06T16:23:01.8903502Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105840/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105840/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-03","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 6 May 2014, to the hon. Member for Islington South and Finsbury to Question 197359, if he will make it his policy that HM Revenue and Customs collects statistics at a regional level for the purposes of completed inspections and non-compliance.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","212932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105841","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-06","<p>Since 1 October 2013 the Government has named 30 employers under the revised scheme. Between them they owed workers a total of over £50,000 in arrears and have been charged financial penalties totalling over £24,000. We will be naming other employers that break National Minimum Wage law very soon.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These employers were named in two separate press notices (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/government-names-employers-who-fail-to-pay-minimum-wage" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/government-names-employers-who-fail-to-pay-minimum-wage</a> and <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/government-gets-tough-with-employers-failing-to-pay-minimum-wage" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/government-gets-tough-with-employers-failing-to-pay-minimum-wage</a>). Five employers were named in February 2014 and 25 employers were named in June 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Any worker who believes that they are being paid below the minimum wage should call the Pay &amp; Work Rights Helpline on 0800 917 2368. HM Revenue &amp; Customs investigate all complaints.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-11-06T17:36:18.0182623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105841/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105841/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-03","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many employers were named for breaking the National Minimum Wage Act 1998 in each month of 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","212933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105842","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-10","<p>A statistical release covering take-up of the Employment Allowance, including regional and constituency data was published on the 7<sup>th</sup> November.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These statistics show that up to October 5<sup>th</sup> 2014, midway through the 2014-15 tax year, 35,000 employers in Wales and 728,000 employers in England had claimed and benefitted from the Employment Allowance. Employers automatically benefit from the allowance if they make a claim and have an employer Class 1 National Insurance Contribution bill.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>So far 900 employers in Aberconwy and 6,400 employers in the North Wales constituencies have benefitted from the Employment Allowance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This demonstrates the Government’s commitment to reducing the costs of employment for small businesses across the UK.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","212884","2014-11-10T17:56:37.4291278Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105842/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105842/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-03","National Insurance Contributions: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many businesses have (a) claimed and (b) been awarded employment allowance in (i) Aberconwy, (ii) Conwy and (iii) North Wales in the last year.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","212969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105843","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-13","<p><strong>Treasury ministers have discussions with the Northern Ireland Executive from time to time on a range of financial issues.</strong></p><p> </p>","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Danny Alexander",,"2014-11-13T11:06:59.1412909Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105843/answer","Biography information for Danny Alexander","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105843/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-03","Economic Situation: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions he has had with the Northern Ireland Executive on its financial position.","false","Biography information for Sir Jeffrey M. Donaldson","Lagan Valley","Mr Jeffrey M. Donaldson","212912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105844","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-20","<p>Details of the Chancellors meetings are published in HMT transparency returns.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government’s shareholding in Lloyds is managed at arm’s length from HM Treasury by UK Financial Investments Ltd. In accordance with UKFI’s investment mandate, the Government does not seek to intervene in the operational management of Lloyds Banking Group.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-11-20T13:50:57.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105844/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105844/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-03","Lloyds Banking Group","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with Lloyds Bank since its announcement of 9,000 job losses.","false","Biography information for Lord McCrea of Magherafelt and Cookstown","South Antrim","Dr William McCrea","212921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105845","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-11","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the Answer the Minister of State for the Cabinet Office gave him on 10 November 2014, Parliamentary UIN 213040</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-11-11T16:41:32.6718142Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105845/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105845/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-03","Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on how many occasions his Department has had requests for appointments by exception to the Senior Civil Service turned down by the Civil Service Commission since 2010; and who was appointed for each such post.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105846","HM Treasury","false","2015-02-02","<p>The Civil Service Commission publish details of appointments made by exception and approved by them in their annual reports and on their website. These reports are also available in the Library of the House.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-02-02T14:16:04.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105846/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105846/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-03","Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on how many occasions his Department has made appointments by exception since 2010; and who was appointed for each such post.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105847","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Ministry of Justice (MOJ) publishes quarterly statistics bulletins on departments’ handling of FOI requests. These bulletins include tables showing how many requests were granted in full, or resulted in some or all information being withheld.</p><p> </p><p>The MOJ statistics bulletin can be found at:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/government-foi-statistics</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-11-10T17:52:29.74514Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105847/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105847/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-03","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many Freedom of Information requests his Department has declined to answer in full since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105848","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-10","<p>The changing technological landscape is not expected to have a negative net impact on employment growth in the wider economy over the next five to 10 years. It is difficult to reliably estimate the number of jobs which could be displaced by technological change. New technology opens up new job opportunities, the Warwick University Working Futures projections, based on past trends, indicate 1.9 million additional jobs growth for the whole economy and a greater than 20% increase in jobs in Information Technology sectors between 2012 and 2022<sup> [1]</sup>. Through initiatives like the Your Life campaign, we are ensuring the supply of future talent.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>1 <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/298510/working-futures-2012-2022-main-report.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/298510/working-futures-2012-2022-main-report.pdf</a></p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-11-10T14:06:56.819889Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105848/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105848/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-03","Technology: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will estimate the number of jobs which will be displaced by technological change in the next (a) five and (b) 10 years.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","213000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105849","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-10","<p>The spend on legal fees in relation to Freedom of Information requests is not separately recorded in the department’s accounts system.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-11-10T17:51:14.2188158Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105849/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/105849/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-03","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much his Department has spent on legal fees over prevention of release of information requested by Freedom of Information requests since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213117"
