"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106063","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-06","<p /> <p>No conversations have taken place between the Secretary of State and the Chancellor of the Exchequer about the effects of the no win no fee reforms on insolvency proceedings. Officials are having ongoing discussions with other government departments on issues relating to and arising from the LASPO Act 2012.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-11-06T17:46:52.9596334Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106063/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106063/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-03","Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on the effect of funding changes in insolvency litigation in the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 on HM Revenue and Customs.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Mr Andy Slaughter","212986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106064","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-10","<p /> <p>The number of deaths in prison custody from drug overdoses for the last 3 years is published in the Safety in Custody statistical bulletin which is available at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/collections/safety-in-custody-statistics" target="_blank">http://www.gov.uk/government/collections/safety-in-custody-statistics</a>.</p><p>Table 1.12 of the Deaths in Prison Custody 1978-2013 shows self-inflicted deaths by method.</p><p> </p><p>We are working hard to manage the levels of self-harm in prison and are carefully investigating the rise in self-inflicted deaths.</p><p> </p><p>We are applying strenuous efforts to learn from each one and providing further resources and support to prisons to help support their safer custody work.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-11-10T17:44:29.4672664Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106064/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106064/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-03","Prisons: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners in England and Wales have died from drug overdoses in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Mike Hancock","Portsmouth South","Mr Mike Hancock","212970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106065","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-06","<p>As part of the review of the Incentives and Earned Privileges national policy framework, contracted-out prisons were required to remove subscription television services by 31 July 2013.</p><p> </p><p>It would not be possible to provide the information requested without incurring disproportionate cost. However, I am able to inform the hon Member that, as at 14 September 2012, an estimated 2976 prisoners in contracted-out prisons were eligible to access subscription channels provided by British Sky Broadcasting.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-11-06T16:27:22.8577118Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106065/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106065/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-03","Prisons: Pay Television","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners held in contracted-out prisons were eligible to have access to subscription channels provided by British Sky Broadcasting in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012 and (c) 2013.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","212934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106066","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-10","<p>The number of persons proceeded against at magistrates’ courts, found guilty and fined for offences relating to pedal cycles by gender, age group and police force area in England and Wales, from 2003 to 2013 (the latest available) can be viewed in the table 1.</p><p> </p><p>The number of persons proceeded against at magistrates’ courts, found guilty and fined for offences connected with pedal cycles by gender, age group and court can be viewed in the table 2.</p><p> </p><p>Trend data can be viewed in table 3.</p><p>Data on fixed penalty notices and data on warrants for the arrest of the offender are not held centrally by the Ministry of Justice. Furthermore, data held centrally on the Court Proceedings Database is not available at constituency level.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","212859 ; 212860 ; 212873 ; 212874 ; 212913 ; 212991 ; 212992 ; 212993","2014-11-10T17:16:32.0449805Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106066/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106066/answer","212859-212860-212873-212874-212913-212968-212992-212991-212993 - force table.xlsx ; 212859-212860-212873-212874-212913-212968-212992-212991-212993 - courts table.xlsx ; 212859-212860-212873-212874-212913-212968-212992-212991-212993 - trends table.xls","212859-212860-212873-212874-212913-212968-212992-212991-212993 - force table.xlsx ; 212859-212860-212873-212874-212913-212968-212992-212991-212993 - courts table.xlsx ; 212859-212860-212873-212874-212913-212968-212992-212991-212993 - trends table.xls","cycling offences by police force ; cycling offences by court ; cycling offences trends","cycling offences by police force ; cycling offences by court ; cycling offences trends","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106066/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-03","Cycling: Essex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many cyclists have been prosecuted for wanton and furious cycling in (a) Southend and (b) Essex in each of the last 10 years for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","212968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106067","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>The security of all UK citizens remains this Government’s highest priority. While the threat level in Northern Ireland remains at Severe, excellent co-operation between PSNI and its partners has put violent dissident republicans under strain in recent months. There have been a number of significant arrests, charges and convictions which are helping to suppress the threat.</p><p>This Government has provided additional security funding to the PSNI totalling £231million between 2011 and 2016 in order to support them in tackling this threat.</p><p>The funding the PSNI received from the NI block grant through the Department of Justice also plays an important role in national security work. The Chief Constable has indicated that recent reductions in PSNI funding by the Executive will have an impact on countering the threat from terrorism in NI. I have asked for a full assessment of what that impact is going to be.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-11-10T11:39:16.9155523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106067/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106067/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-11-03","Counter-terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what steps her Department is taking to tackle the dissident republican threat in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","212966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106068","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-11-11","<p>It is important that the sacrifice of those who gave their lives in the World Wars, and other conflicts, is never forgotten and that the memorials to their sacrifice are well maintained.</p><p>The maintenance of local World War memorials is carried out by local authorities across the United Kingdom. Section 1 of the War Memorials (Local Authorities’ Powers) Act 1923 (which extends to Northern Ireland) provides for local authorities to incur reasonable expenditure in the maintenance, repair and protection of any war memorial within their district whether vested in them or not.</p><p>On 1 July 2014, my Rt hon Friends the Prime Minister and the Secretary of State for Culture Media and Sport announced details of a £5 million fund to conserve and protect war memorials. This funding will support a range of different projects including the provision of up to £3 million for the War Memorials Trust which works for the protection and conservation of war memorials within the United Kingdom to ensure they remain part of our communities forever.</p><p>The funding to the War Memorials Trust over the four year period of the First World War Centenary will boost support for their grant schemes and expand their team of specialist Conservation Officers.</p><p> </p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2014-11-11T17:03:49.8397181Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106068/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106068/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-11-03","War Memorials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what steps her Department is taking to support the future refurbishment of World War memorials in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","212952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106069","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>My Department made 96 awards of amounts ranging from £100 to £500 under the Reward and Recognition scheme totalling £11,800 in 2013/14. 2013/14 figures reflect awards made in respect of work associated with the G8 conference.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In 2014, my Department has made 13 awards totalling £3,150 to date.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-11-10T13:21:15.0262288Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106069/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106069/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-11-03","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many Instant Rewards of what value were given to her Department's officials in (a) 2013 and (b) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106070","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Northern Ireland Office pays fees to the Treasury Solicitor’s Department for legal advice on a range of issues. To provide those fees which relate to the Freedom of Information Act 2000 would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-11-10T11:34:31.2929674Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106070/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106070/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-11-03","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how much her Department has spent on legal fees over prevention of release of information requested by Freedom of Information requests since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106071","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Civil Service Commission publish details of appointments made by exception and approved by them in their annual reports and on their website. These reports are available in the Library of the House. It would not be appropriate to publish details of the requests turned down by the Commission as the numbers involved are so small.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-11-10T13:23:39.0502614Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106071/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106071/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-11-03","Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, on how many occasions her Department has had requests for appointments by exception to the Senior Civil Service turned down by the Civil Service Commission since 2010; and who was appointed for each such post.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106072","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Ministry of Justice (MoJ) publish annual statistical reports on the handling of requests for information under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 for central government. They can be accessed via the following webpage:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/government-foi-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/government-foi-statistics</a>.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-11-10T13:26:00.9516234Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106072/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106072/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-11-03","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many Freedom of Information requests her Department has declined to answer in full since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106073","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>My Department made appointments by exception as set out below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Recruitments by Exception</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014/15 to date</strong></p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Records prior to 2012 are not held.</p><p>The Civil Service Commission requires secondments from the NI Civil Service to be listed as an exception. Northern Ireland Civil Servants at grades below Senior Civil Servant were appointed on a secondment basis to all of these posts with the exception of one which was an appointment at SCS Pay Band 1 for the post of Deputy Director, Community Engagement Group. This post was also filled on a secondment basis by a member of the Northern Ireland Civil Service.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-11-10T13:30:49.2621474Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106073/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106073/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-11-03","Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, on how many occasions her Department has made appointments by exception since 2010; and who was appointed for each such post.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213032"
