"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106075","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-07","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office. Information on departments’ handling of FOI requests is published on a quarterly basis by the Ministry of Justice and is available at GOV.UK under the series Government FOI Statistics.</p><p>I refer the hon. Member to the answers I gave on 10 July 2014 to UIN: PQ204306-PQ20470.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","213080 ; 213101 ; 213114","2014-11-07T11:47:52.0634697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106075/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106075/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106075/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-03","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many Freedom of Information requests 10 Downing Street has declined to answer in full since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106076","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office.</p><p>The Civil Service Commission publish details of appointments made by exception and approved by them in their annual reports and on their website. These reports are available in the Library of the House. It would not be appropriate to publish, by Department, details of the requests turned down by the Commission as the numbers involved are so small.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","213040","2014-11-10T14:52:51.2706328Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106076/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106076/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-03","Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, on how many occasions 10 Downing Street has had requests for appointments by exception to the Senior Civil Service turned down by the Civil Service Commission since 2010; and who was appointed for each such post.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106077","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office.</p><p>Cabinet Office makes appointments on merit on the basis of fair and open competition in compliance with the Civil Service Commission’s Recruitment Principles.</p><p>Other appointments are made using permitted exceptions to the Civil Service Commission’s Recruitment Principles to support Apprenticeship and Graduate Internship schemes, commercial interchange, short term projects and other specific business needs.</p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>47</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>78</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>126</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>94</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014- 31/10/14</p></td><td><p>110</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>In line with the practice of the previous administration the names of individuals have not been provided to protect their identities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","213020","2014-11-10T17:42:36.9547525Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106077/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106077/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-03","Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, on how many occasions 10 Downing Street has made appointments by exception since 2010; and who was appointed for each such post.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106078","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-06","<p>The Government awards contracts on the basis of the best overall value for money for the taxpayer. We encourage contractors to commit to paying a living wage. Previous governments did not create a blanket requirement for contractors to pay a living wage.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-11-06T17:58:15.9214274Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106078/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106078/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106078/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-03","Government Departments: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make it his policy that cleaners of all Government offices are paid the living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","213135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106079","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-07","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office. Information on departments’ handling of FOI requests is published on a quarterly basis by the Ministry of Justice and is available at GOV.UK under the series Government FOI Statistics.</p><p>I refer the hon. Member to the answers I gave on 10 July 2014 to UIN: PQ204306-PQ20470.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","213080 ; 213093 ; 213101","2014-11-07T11:47:52.2514598Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106079/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106079/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106079/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-03","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much 10 Downing Street has spent on legal fees over prevention of release of information requested by Freedom of Information requests since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106080","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office. The Cabinet Office does not provide Instant Rewards.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","213060","2014-11-10T14:55:41.3473503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106080/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106080/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106080/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-03","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many Instant Rewards of what value were given to 10 Downing Street officials in (a) 2013 and (b) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106081","Prime Minister","false","2014-11-07","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to him on 5 November 2014, <em>Official Report</em>, column 819.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2014-11-07T12:13:42.747323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106081/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106081/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106081/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2014-11-03","Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, when he next plans to visit Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","212904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106082","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-11","<p>In <em>‘Building a Prosperous and United Community’</em> the Government Committed to make a decision on whether to devolve corporation tax powers to Northern Ireland no later than Autumn Statement 2014. Significant legislative and technical work has taken place to date and we remain on track to meet this timetable.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-11-11T17:07:00.0602942Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106082/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106082/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106082/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-03","Corporation Tax: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to give the Northern Ireland Assembly power to vary the level of corporation tax in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","212905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106083","Prime Minister","false","2014-11-07","<p>I discussed the issue of terrorist financing with His Highness The Emir, and the role that both our countries can play to tackle it. I welcomed the recent legislation to prevent terrorist funding in Qatar by regulating charities that are involved in politics or send money abroad and encouraged swift implementation of this legislation. We agreed to increase cooperation on sharing information on groups of concern.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2014-11-07T12:15:33.5368505Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106083/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106083/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106083/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2014-11-03","Qatar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether he raised the funding of the al-Nusra Front with the Emir of Qatar during his meeting on 29 October 2014; and what agreement was reached at that meeting on co-operation between the UK and Qatar to stop the illegal funding of terrorist groups in Syria and Iraq by Qatari nationals.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","212891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106084","Scotland Office","false","2014-11-11","<p>Instant Rewards were given to Scotland Office officials as follows in 2013 and 2014; (a) one award of £50, and (b) nil to date.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2014-11-11T12:40:11.8144506Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106084/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106084/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106084/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-11-03","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many Instant Rewards of what value were given to his Department's officials in (a) 2013 and (b) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106085","Scotland Office","false","2014-11-05","<p>The Scotland Office has incurred no expenditure on legal fees over prevention of release of information requested by Freedom of Information requests since 2010.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2014-11-05T15:51:56.2416918Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106085/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106085/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106085/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-11-03","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how much his Department has spent on legal fees over prevention of release of information requested by Freedom of Information requests since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106086","Scotland Office","false","2014-11-11","<p>The Civil Service Commission publish details of appointments made by exception and approved by them in their annual reports and on their website. These reports are available in the Library of the House. It would not be appropriate to publish details of the requests turned down by the Commission as the numbers involved are so small.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2014-11-11T12:45:22.9279835Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106086/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106086/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-11-03","Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, on how many occasions his Department has made appointments by exception since 2010; and who was appointed for each such post.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106087","Scotland Office","false","2014-11-11","<p>The Civil Service Commission publish details of appointments made by exception and approved by them in their annual reports and on their website. These reports are available in the Library of the House. It would not be appropriate to publish details of the requests turned down by the Commission as the numbers involved are so small.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2014-11-11T12:47:04.1292146Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106087/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106087/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-11-03","Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, on how many occasions his Department has had requests for appointments by exception to the Senior Civil Service turned down by the Civil Service Commission since 2010; and who was appointed for each such post.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106088","Scotland Office","false","2014-11-05","<p>Since 2010 and up to the end of September 2014, the Scotland Office has answered 343 Freedom of Information requests in full out of 678 received. The other requests were not answered in full for a variety of reasons: the request may have been unclear, the Scotland Office may not have held the information, the request may have been exempt under the Freedom of Information Act 2000, or the cost of locating the information may have exceeded the appropriate limit under the Act. Where the request was not granted in full it may have been answered in part.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2014-11-05T15:54:40.0925307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106088/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106088/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-11-03","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many Freedom of Information requests his Department has declined to answer in full since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106089","Scotland Office","false","2014-11-05","<p>The Scotland Office has incurred no expenditure on iPhones in any year since 2010.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2014-11-05T15:56:28.543744Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106089/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106089/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-11-03","Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how much his Department spent on iPhones in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106090","Members Estimate Committee","false","2014-11-06","<p>The House of Commons Commission (which was responsible for Members Estimate matters prior to the establishment of the Members Estimate Committee in 2004) agreed at its meeting of 21 October 2002 to implement a retention policy for financial papers, which would entail detailed claims, receipts, invoices and warrants being retained for three years after the end of the year of the transaction. This included documentation relating to Members’ allowances. The policy was incorporated into the Authorised Records Disposal Practice (ARDP) produced by the Parliamentary Archives and made available to Members and staff of both Houses on the parliamentary intranet in 2004. Decisions made by the House of Commons Commission and the Members Estimate Committee are published on the Parliament website.</p><p>Destruction of these records was paused in 2010 pending the conclusion of police inquiries, but was restarted on the previous basis in 2012 once legal proceedings were concluded. The only documentation destroyed in the last 12 months in relation to Members’ expenses has been background information to support claims, which was no longer needed after the 2010 general election when the House ceased to be responsible for expenses claims. This was done in April 2014.</p><p>While the original financial documents relating to MPs’ expenses were destroyed in compliance with the Authorised Records Disposal Policy (ARDP), more than a million documents and receipts, with some personal information redacted, were published online and subsequently updated. This information remains available on the Parliament website at: <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/mps-lords-and-offices/members-allowances/house-of-commons/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/mps-lords-and-offices/members-allowances/house-of-commons/</a>.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso","213009 ; 213010","2014-11-06T15:11:56.6410126Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106090/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106090/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106090/answer",,,,,"91","Members Estimate Committee","Members Estimate Committee","2014-11-03","Members: Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross, representing the Members Estimate Committee, when it was determined to shred documentation on expenses claims submitted by hon. Members before 2010; and at what committee or decision-making body such a decision was taken.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","213008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106091","Members Estimate Committee","false","2014-11-06","<p>The House of Commons Commission (which was responsible for Members Estimate matters prior to the establishment of the Members Estimate Committee in 2004) agreed at its meeting of 21 October 2002 to implement a retention policy for financial papers, which would entail detailed claims, receipts, invoices and warrants being retained for three years after the end of the year of the transaction. This included documentation relating to Members’ allowances. The policy was incorporated into the Authorised Records Disposal Practice (ARDP) produced by the Parliamentary Archives and made available to Members and staff of both Houses on the parliamentary intranet in 2004. Decisions made by the House of Commons Commission and the Members Estimate Committee are published on the Parliament website.</p><p>Destruction of these records was paused in 2010 pending the conclusion of police inquiries, but was restarted on the previous basis in 2012 once legal proceedings were concluded. The only documentation destroyed in the last 12 months in relation to Members’ expenses has been background information to support claims, which was no longer needed after the 2010 general election when the House ceased to be responsible for expenses claims. This was done in April 2014.</p><p>While the original financial documents relating to MPs’ expenses were destroyed in compliance with the Authorised Records Disposal Policy (ARDP), more than a million documents and receipts, with some personal information redacted, were published online and subsequently updated. This information remains available on the Parliament website at: <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/mps-lords-and-offices/members-allowances/house-of-commons/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/mps-lords-and-offices/members-allowances/house-of-commons/</a>.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso","213008 ; 213010","2014-11-06T15:11:56.9066587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106091/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106091/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106091/answer",,,,,"91","Members Estimate Committee","Members Estimate Committee","2014-11-03","Members: Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross, representing the Members Estimate Committee, which documentation relating to expenses claims submitted by hon. Members in which years have been shredded in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","213009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106092","Members Estimate Committee","false","2014-11-06","<p>The House of Commons Commission (which was responsible for Members Estimate matters prior to the establishment of the Members Estimate Committee in 2004) agreed at its meeting of 21 October 2002 to implement a retention policy for financial papers, which would entail detailed claims, receipts, invoices and warrants being retained for three years after the end of the year of the transaction. This included documentation relating to Members’ allowances. The policy was incorporated into the Authorised Records Disposal Practice (ARDP) produced by the Parliamentary Archives and made available to Members and staff of both Houses on the parliamentary intranet in 2004. Decisions made by the House of Commons Commission and the Members Estimate Committee are published on the Parliament website.</p><p>Destruction of these records was paused in 2010 pending the conclusion of police inquiries, but was restarted on the previous basis in 2012 once legal proceedings were concluded. The only documentation destroyed in the last 12 months in relation to Members’ expenses has been background information to support claims, which was no longer needed after the 2010 general election when the House ceased to be responsible for expenses claims. This was done in April 2014.</p><p>While the original financial documents relating to MPs’ expenses were destroyed in compliance with the Authorised Records Disposal Policy (ARDP), more than a million documents and receipts, with some personal information redacted, were published online and subsequently updated. This information remains available on the Parliament website at: <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/mps-lords-and-offices/members-allowances/house-of-commons/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/mps-lords-and-offices/members-allowances/house-of-commons/</a>.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso","213008 ; 213009","2014-11-06T15:11:57.0051776Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106092/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106092/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106092/answer",,,,,"91","Members Estimate Committee","Members Estimate Committee","2014-11-03","Members: Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross, representing the Members Estimate Committee, when the decision to destroy documentation relating to hon. Members' expenses claims from before 2010 was reported to the House.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","213010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106093","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2014-11-06","<p>The Commission informs me that its reports on the accuracy and completeness of the electoral registers set out possible reasons why people may fail to register to vote. These reports are available on the Commission’s website.</p><p> </p><p>The Commission also conducts public opinion research after each set of elections that asks non-voters why they did not vote at the recent election. The results from these polls are also available on the Commission’s website.</p><p> </p>","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter",,"2014-11-06T14:47:36.5589899Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106093/answer","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106093/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106093/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2014-11-03","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for South West Devon, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, what recent research the Electoral Commission has conducted into the reasons why individuals who are (a) entitled to vote do not register and (b) on the electoral register do not vote.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","212987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106094","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2014-11-06","<p>The Electoral Commission does not set out to increase the take-up of postal voting and instead provides information to help people participate with confidence in elections and referendums by whatever method they find most convenient. This includes ensuring people understand the range of options available to them to cast their vote, including by post, proxy and at a polling station.</p><p> </p><p>The Commission’s guidance to Electoral Registration Officers sets out that they should ensure people are made aware of the different ways they can cast their vote so they are able to choose the option that is most appropriate to their circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>Information on different options for how to cast a ballot is also provided on the Commission’s website, via media releases, social media channels, and through the public information phone line.</p><p> </p>","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter",,"2014-11-06T14:49:20.8572732Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106094/answer","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106094/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106094/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2014-11-03","Absent Voting","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for South West Devon, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, what steps the Electoral Commission is taking to increase the take-up of postal votes.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","213172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106095","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-06","<p>The National Maritime Information Centre (NMIC) is reporting to interested government departments the movement and expected arrival information of vessels that have been in ports or anchorages in Guinea, Liberia or Sierra Leone within the Ebola incubation period (21 days). This information is made available to the ports and shipping communities, including port health authorities.</p><p> </p><p>There are six ships on the current Vessels of Interest (VoI) list which have, within the last 21 days, visited ports in the three countries affected by the Ebola outbreak. A total of 67 VoIs has been identified in the last two months. Most of these vessels have not called at a UK port but were rather travelling to neighbouring countries. Of these vessels, none have been identified as having any symptoms of Ebola like virus on board.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-11-06T14:28:16.5628917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106095/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106095/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106095/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Ebola","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what function the National Maritime Intelligence Organisation's Vessels of Interest (VOI) list performs in alerting ports to ships with potential cases of Ebola onboard; and how many ships have been listed on the VOI list in the last two months because of possible Ebola cases.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Mr Gordon Marsden","213173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106096","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-06","<p>In October 2014, guidance titled &quot;West Africa Ebola Outbreak – Guidance to UK Ports and Shipping Operators&quot; was produced in consultation with the Maritime and Coastguard Agency’s medical advisor and Public Health England. Work on additional guidance, which is being produced in consultation with Public Health England, the Maritime and Coastguard Agency and industry has been under way for some time, and I have asked for this to be made available as soon as possible.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-11-06T14:29:09.2835699Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106096/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106096/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106096/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Ebola","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what guidance his Department has produced for people working in port pilotage on protocol for dealing with ships entering the UK from regions affected by the Ebola virus.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Mr Gordon Marsden","213174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106097","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-06","<p>Port Health Officers routinely check declarations of health on arrival.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-11-06T14:29:52.5794439Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106097/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106097/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106097/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Ebola","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what independent checks are made on the validity of reports on crew health which ships submit to the Maritime and Coastguard Agency on entering UK waters.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Mr Gordon Marsden","213175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106098","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-06","<p>I have asked officials at the MCA whether they need any more resources to support their work on the response to the Ebola outbreak in West Africa. Thus far, work on this has been carried out under normal operating procedures.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-11-06T14:30:36.6268645Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106098/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106098/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106098/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Ebola","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether extra resources have been made available to the Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) to support its response to the Ebola outbreak; and what estimate he has made of the number of staff hours in the MCA which have been spent on responding to the Ebola outbreak.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Mr Gordon Marsden","213176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106099","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-10","<p>The amount spent by this Department and its Executive Agencies on external legal fees in relation to withholding information requested under the Freedom of Information Act 2000, namely payments to the Treasury Solicitor’s Department and counsel, in each of the last five financial years, is as shown in the table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year</p><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>External legal spend (excluding VAT)</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>£17,495</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>£32,404</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>£311</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>£3,068</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>£69</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>£38,475</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-11-10T16:13:56.2385401Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106099/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106099/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106099/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much his Department has spent on legal fees over prevention of release of information requested by Freedom of Information requests since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106100","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Department for Transport and its executive agencies spend (all figures are net of VAT) on iPhones in each year since 2010 is in the table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p>Year</p><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p>DfT iPhone spend</p><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p>2010</p><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>Nil</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p>2011</p><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>Nil</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p>2012</p><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>£1,425</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p>2013</p><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>£22,265</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p>2014</p><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>£15,905</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p>Total</p><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p>£39,595</p><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong><strong></strong></strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The majority of the spend has been incurred by the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency.　This is as part of its new operating model ‘Next Generation Testing’, with the need to ensure staff have immediate access to support functions whilst they are working remotely.　This includes the ability to visually and audibly show vehicle defects when having conversations with technical support specialists, with live video and interaction supported through the 'facetime' functionality, and access to electronic manuals and technical information on the move.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-11-10T16:12:49.4649923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106100/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106100/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106100/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much his Department spent on iPhones in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106101","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-10","<p>The MOT test does not, as a matter of principle, involve modifying the vehicles tested in any way. This is in part to ensure that the vehicle owner can have confidence that their vehicle is not damaged by the test. We would be happy to consider proposals to make enforcement against noisy motorcyclists easier. It is doubtful a mandatory seal is a practical and proportionate measure, as many motorcyclists need to make legitimate repairs or modifications to their exhausts between annual tests.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-11-10T11:15:15.4045074Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106101/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106101/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106101/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Motorcycles: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October 2014 to Question 211087, if he will bring forward proposals to prevent, by means of (a) a mandatory seal and (b) other measures motorcyclists tampering with their exhausts after passing the MOT noise test.","false","Biography information for Eric Ollerenshaw","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Eric Ollerenshaw","212947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106102","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-06","<p>The Department’s THINK! Education resource centre provides education resources, which are organised into lesson packs by age and stages of education.</p><p> </p><p>The Government also has a number of public facing web pages and social media sites such as &quot;Tales of the Road&quot;, which features: road safety games, quizzes, tips and advice for 6-11 year olds and their parents; and &quot;I can’t wait to pass my driving test&quot;, which has lots of useful information for learning to drive.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises that there is value in training cyclists to ride safely and confidently on the road. That is why we took the decision to safeguard the future of Bikeability during this Parliament.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-11-06T16:07:47.1908546Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106102/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106102/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106102/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Roads: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to educate young people on road safety.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","212967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106103","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-06","<p>Under devolution, East London river crossings are primarily a matter for the Mayor and Transport for London. In designating the Silvertown Tunnel as a Nationally Significant Infrastructure Project, this Government has recognised the importance of river-crossing infrastructure to the effective functioning of the strategic road network, and the continued successful development of East London's economy.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has made no assessment of new river crossings on the economy of East London. However, Transport for London has published information to support a consultation currently underway on the Silvertown Tunnel, which sets out the value of that scheme to the local economy. The recently concluded consultation on options for new crossings further east included a similar assessment. Both can be found on Transport for London’s consultation website: <a href="https://consultations.tfl.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://consultations.tfl.gov.uk/</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-11-06T14:35:07.1352701Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106103/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106103/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106103/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","River Thames: Bridges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of new river crossings in East London on the economy of that area.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","212892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106104","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-13","<p>The Government is committed to improving the local road network. Road improvements in Wales are a devolved matter and therefore the responsibility of the Welsh Government.</p><p> </p><p>The attached table includes funding we have provided through the local Highways Maintenance Block, Integrated Transport Block, Severe Weather Funding, Local Major Projects and Local Pinch Point Fund schemes. The table does not include funding provided through the Bus Service Operators Grant, Local Sustainable Transport Fund, or Cycling Grant.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is also funding local highways maintenance projects in Portsmouth, Birmingham, Sheffield, Isle of Wight and the London Borough of Hounslow through the Private Finance Initiative.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities are also able to use revenue funding, allocated by the Department of Communities and Local Government through the Revenue Support Grant for maintaining their local highways. It is for local highway authorities to decide upon their spending priorities across the whole range of services that they provide.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-11-13T13:37:51.8797455Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106104/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106104/answer","141113 - UIN 212882 - Funding Allocated to Each Local Authority for Road Improvements in Each Year Since 2010.doc","141113 - UIN 212882 - Funding Allocated to Each Local Authority for Road Improvements in Each Year Since 2010.doc","212882_Funding allocated for road improvements","212882_Funding allocated for road improvements","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106104/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much funding his Department has allocated to each local authority in England and Wales for road improvement in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr David Ruffley","Bury St Edmunds","Mr David Ruffley","212882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106105","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Department for Transport has allocated the following amounts to the local transport authority in Suffolk for the years for which figures are available:</p><table><tbody><tr><td>Year</td><td>£million</td><td>£ per mile of road length</td><td>£ per head of population</td></tr><tr><td>2000/01</td><td>8.472</td><td>2,063</td><td>13</td></tr><tr><td>2001/02</td><td>20.967</td><td>5,097</td><td>31</td></tr><tr><td>2002/03</td><td>19.958</td><td>4,773</td><td>30</td></tr><tr><td>2003/04</td><td>20.566</td><td>4,910</td><td>30</td></tr><tr><td>2004/05</td><td>22.230</td><td>5,331</td><td>32</td></tr><tr><td>2005/06</td><td>22.624</td><td>5,424</td><td>32</td></tr><tr><td>2006/07</td><td>23.610</td><td>5,559</td><td>34</td></tr><tr><td>2007/08</td><td>21.745</td><td>5,113</td><td>31</td></tr><tr><td>2008/09</td><td>29.834</td><td>7,011</td><td>42</td></tr><tr><td>2009/10</td><td>26.894</td><td>6,333</td><td>37</td></tr><tr><td>2010/11</td><td>23.155</td><td>5,448</td><td>32</td></tr><tr><td>2011/12</td><td>27.924</td><td>6.566</td><td>38</td></tr><tr><td>2012/13</td><td>30.304</td><td>7.123</td><td>41</td></tr><tr><td>2013/14</td><td>35.513</td><td>8,341</td><td>48</td></tr><tr><td>2014/15</td><td>37.523</td><td>8,813</td><td>51</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Note: population and road lengths data are not available for 2014. Figures for 2013 have been used to calculate the £ per mile and £ per head in 2014.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-11-10T16:56:57.2792074Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106105/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106105/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106105/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Transport: Suffolk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much funding his Department gave to the local transport authority in Suffolk (a) in total, (b) per mile of road in the local authority area and (c) per head of population in that area in each year since 1997.","false","Biography information for Mr David Ruffley","Bury St Edmunds","Mr David Ruffley","212883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106106","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-10","<p>Domestic services to Ashford and intermediate stations are provided by the franchised operator London and Southeastern Railway Limited (&quot;Southeastern&quot;). The level of service provided is specified in Southeastern’s franchise agreement and would not be directly affected by the sale of the Government’s holding in Eurostar.</p><p> </p><p>Eurostar is an open access operator; any decision on services provided by Eurostar to Ashford or intermediate stations is a commercial matter for that operator.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-11-10T11:13:35.6338284Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106106/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106106/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106106/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Channel Tunnel Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to protect High Speed services to Ashford and other intermediate stations after the sale of the Government's shareholding in Eurostar; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Damian Green","Ashford","Damian Green","212973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106107","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-10","<p>Statistics on the number of Freedom of Information (FOI) requests answered by the Department for Transport are published by the Ministry of Justice. The published figures include information on the number of requests where the Department withheld some or all of the requested information. These reports can be accessed on the following webpage:</p><p /> <p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/government-foi-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/government-foi-statistics</a></p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-11-10T16:19:24.6303486Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106107/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106107/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106107/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many Freedom of Information requests his Department has declined to answer in full since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106108","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-06","<p>The number of reported road deaths in Great Britain in the last 5 years is shown in the table below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Year </strong></td><td><strong>Road deaths </strong></td></tr><tr><td>2009</td><td>2,222</td></tr><tr><td>2010</td><td>1,850</td></tr><tr><td>2011</td><td>1,901</td></tr><tr><td>2012</td><td>1,754</td></tr><tr><td>2013</td><td>1,713</td></tr></tbody></table><p>In addition the Q1 2014 reported fatalities were published on 7 August 2014 whilst the Q2 statistics were published on 6 November 2014. They can be found at</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/road-accidents-and-safety-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/road-accidents-and-safety-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department published its Strategic Framework for Road Safety in May 2011. We have since taken a series of important steps to implement proposals set out in the framework. They include steps on all three of the thematic chapters of the framework namely improving road safety together, education, and targeted enforcement and sanctions. Further information on the progress can be found in my recent speech to the Road Safety Foundation at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/making-road-safety-pay" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/making-road-safety-pay</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-11-06T16:06:15.5287647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106108/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106108/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106108/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Roads: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many road deaths there have been in the last five years; and what steps his Department is taking to reduce such deaths.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","213124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106109","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-11","<p>As reported in the Civil Service Commissioners Audit report, the number of appointments made by exception since 2010 are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Year</strong></td><td><strong>Number of exceptions</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong> </strong></td><td><strong>Grade 6 and below</strong></td></tr><tr><td>2010/11</td><td>220</td></tr><tr><td rowspan="3">2011/12</td><td>No appointments were made by exception during the year within the Department and its agencies,</td></tr><tr><td>although it is possible that some former Civil Servants (below SCS Level 2) may have</td></tr><tr><td>been re-appointed under Exception 5, Re appointment of former Civil Servants</td></tr><tr><td>2012/13</td><td>31</td></tr><tr><td>2103/14</td><td>29</td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Information on who was appointed to each post is not held centrally.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-11-11T10:51:27.8642988Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106109/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106109/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106109/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, on how many occasions his Department has made appointments by exception since 2010; and who was appointed for each such post.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106110","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-10","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer given to Question 213040 by my Rt Hon Friend, the Minister for the Cabinet Office (Mr Maude) today.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-11-10T16:08:42.6115575Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106110/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106110/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106110/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, on how many occasions his Department has had requests for appointments by exception to the Senior Civil Service turned down by the Civil Service Commission since 2010; and who was appointed for each such post.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106111","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-06","<p>The table below shows the percentage of all trips made by bicycle between 2009 and 2013:</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6">Average number of trips (trip rates) by main mode: England, to 2013</td></tr><tr><td> </td><td><strong>2009 </strong></td><td><strong>2010 </strong></td><td><strong>2011 </strong></td><td><strong>2012 </strong></td><td><strong>2013 </strong></td></tr><tr><td>Bicycle</td><td>16</td><td>15</td><td>16</td><td>17</td><td>14</td></tr><tr><td>All modes</td><td>974</td><td>961</td><td>950</td><td>950</td><td>923</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Cycling mode share % </strong></td><td><strong>1.7 </strong></td><td><strong>1.6 </strong></td><td><strong>1.7 </strong></td><td><strong>1.8 </strong></td><td><strong>1.9 </strong></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Soure: NTS, Last updated: 29 July 2014</em></p><p>During the five financial years 2010/11 to 2014/15, departmental spending on cycling is detailed in the table below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Financial years 2010/11 - 2014/15 </strong></td><td> </td><td rowspan="11">Direct funding £224 million</td></tr><tr><td> </td><td><strong>£million</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Cycling Englad</td><td>63.0</td></tr><tr><td>Cycling Cities &amp; National Parks Fund</td><td>94.0</td></tr><tr><td>Links to Schools &amp; Linking Communities</td><td>28.5</td></tr><tr><td>Cycle Safety Fund</td><td>35.0</td></tr><tr><td>Cycle Rail</td><td>14.5</td></tr><tr><td>Highways Agency</td><td>4.8</td></tr><tr><td>Local Sustainable Transport Fund - Bikeability</td><td>46.8</td></tr><tr><td>Local Sustainable Transport Fund - other cycling</td><td>151.0</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Total</strong></td><td><strong>437.6</strong></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The £438 million on cycling spend represents 0.71% of the total departmental spend for those years.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-11-06T13:18:21.242377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106111/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106111/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106111/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of passenger journeys in the UK were made by bicycle in each of the last five years; and what share of his Department's spending related to cycling in that time period.","false","Biography information for Alison McGovern","Wirral South","Alison McGovern","213147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106112","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-10","<p>The number of Instant Rewards awarded to employees in the Department for Transport, and the total amount spent in (a) 2013 and (b) 2014 is shown in the table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td>Financial Year</td><td>Number of staff</td><td>Total Spend</td></tr><tr><td>2013/14</td><td>2,079</td><td>£774,138</td></tr><tr><td>2014/15</td><td>981</td><td>£404,780</td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>In 2013 the Department increased the size of the available pot for Instant Rewards following the decision to only pay end of year non-consolidated performance payments to the top 25% of employees. This has reduced the overall spend on non-consolidated performance payments by c. £1.4m.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-11-10T16:11:35.9001896Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106112/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106112/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106112/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-03","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many Instant Rewards of what value were given to his Department's officials in (a) 2013 and (b) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","213075"
