"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102033","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-06","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) continues to make excellent progress in implementing the recommendations of Sir John Holmes's Medals Review. For example, the Prime Minister recently presented South Atlantic Medals to those personnel who became eligible under the change of criteria recommended by Sir John. In addition, the MOD Medal Office has issued in excess of 13,000 Arctic Stars and over 7,000 Bomber Command Clasps.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-11-06T17:49:15.9588772Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102033/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102033/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102033/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102033/answer/previousversion/26464","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-10-31","Military Medals Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what progress has been made in implementing the recommendations of the Sir John Holmes' independent Military Medals Review.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","212798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102034","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-06","<p>Operational and Gallantry Medal awards for our Reserve Forces are judged under the same criteria as those for their Regular counterparts. The difference between awards for Reserve and Regular service is in relation to length of service.</p><p>The Volunteer Reserves Service Medal (VRSM) can be awarded to all Volunteer Reserve personnel after 10 years service. The Long Service and Good Conduct medal can be awarded to regular personnel below the rank of officer after 15 years exemplary service.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-11-06T17:48:42.9570981Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102034/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102034/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102034/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102034/answer/previousversion/26465","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-10-31","Military Decorations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on what criteria applications for service medals for auxiliary personnel are judged.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","212834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102035","Department for Education","false","2014-11-05","<p>Schools and local authorities are responsible for the recruitment of their supply teachers and deciding whether to use private supply agencies to recruit and employ supply teachers. If a supply teacher is employed by a private agency, this is a private commercial arrangement between the school and the agency.</p><p>The Department for Education is not responsible for the regulation of teacher supply agencies or their umbrella organisations. Teacher supply agencies are regulated by the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills under the employment agency provisions in the Employment Agencies Act 1973 and the Conduct of Employment Agencies and Employment Businesses Regulations 2003.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-11-05T16:14:02.8192924Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102035/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102035/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102035/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-10-31","Supply Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her Department's policy is on the use of umbrella companies for supply teachers.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","Mr John Spellar","212792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102036","Department for Education","false","2014-11-06","<p>The Department for Education’s System Accountability Statement is currently under routine review. We expect to publish an update to the existing statement by the end of the year.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-11-06T16:16:31.0588363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102036/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102036/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102036/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-10-31","Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she plans to update the Accountability System Statement outlining the roles and responsibilities for school oversight.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","212821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102037","Department for Education","false","2014-11-07","<p>The Department for Education currently collects information on children looked after by local authorities in England who went missing from their agreed placement for a period of 24 hours or more.</p><p> </p><p>The table attached shows the number of children who went missing from their agreed placement whilst looked after by Hampshire, Portsmouth or Southampton local authority, during the years ending 31 March 2012 to 2014. Children who went missing on more than one occasion during the year have been recorded only once for that year. The table also shows the number of these children who were still missing at 31 March 2014, the latest date for which data are available. In addition to these, there will also be some children who have turned 18, and therefore ceased to be looked after whilst missing. In such cases, information is not collected on whether these young people are still missing.</p><p> </p><p>Comparisons with other data sources, including numbers of missing children reported to the police, indicate that the number of children missing from their agreed placement may be an undercount of the true figure and should be treated with caution. Extensive work on improving the quality of this data has been undertaken during the past two years’ data collections. An increase in the number of children missing from their agreed placement over recent years may therefore be due to improved recording rather than a true increase. From 2015, the information will be collected differently to improve the quality.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson","212803 ; 212805","2014-11-07T13:59:06.250768Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102037/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102037/answer","212803-table_of_missing_children_looked_after_2012-2014.doc","212803-table_of_missing_children_looked_after_2012-2014.doc","Tab